Time Series Analysis Spring 2023

14. Multivariate volatility modelling

Maciej Świtała

01/06/2022

Revision of theoretical background

Main idea

GARCH -> estimating returns (MEAN equation) as well as returns volatility (VARIANCE equation).

Many series -> many GARCHs? Alternative is:

  1. many MEAN equations (for many series):

\[u_t = some ARMA process + a_t\]

where: * u_t = conditional expectation of returns (knowing some past information), * a_t - unexpected return, residual, shock, innovation…

  1. conditional (knowing some past information) COVARIANCE MATRIX of unexpected returns:
# sigma_t = [ σ_1^2,  σ_{12}, ...,  σ_{1n} ]
#           [ σ_{21}, σ_2^2,  ...,  σ_{2n} ]
#           [ ...,    ...,    ...,  ...    ]
#           [ σ_{n1}, σ_{n2}, ...,  σ_n^2  ]

where: * σ_i^2 = var(i) - variance of variable i, * σ_{ij} = cov(i,j) - covariance of variables i and j, * cov(i,j) = E[(i-Ei)*(j-Ej)] = E(ij) - Ei Ej, * var(i) = cov(i,i) = E(i^2) - [Ei]^2, * E denotes expected value.

By the way, covariance is an expected value of multiplied deviations (so in fact, it stands for correlation).

Pearson’s correlation(i,j) = cov(i,j)/(σ_i*σ_j)

Possible approaches

Estimating conditional variance-covariance matrix

Models estimating sigma_t: * EWMA - exponentially weighted moving average, * Diagonal VEC model, * BEKK model.

EWMA: how to estimate sigma_t? * let’s assume equal weight to each shock (questionable)? * let’s assume that recent shocks are more important! \[sigma_t = (1-L)*a_{t-1}*a'_{t-1} + Lsigma_{t-1}\]

Diagonal VEC, BEKK - some other ideas of estimating sigma_t.

GARCH models for bivariate returns

It enables including some more dependencies between conditional variances; evolution of conditional variance over time is mostly considered).

Common models: * CCC - constant conditional correlation, * Time-varying correlation model, * DCC - dynamic conditional correlation.

Main idea: * decomposes the covariance matrix into standard deviations and correlations: \[sigma_t = D_t*R_t*D'_t\] * where: R_t - conditional correlation matrix, D_t - diagonal matrix with standard deviations (common operation in linear algebra, used also in e.g. text mining)

CCC assumes that: R_t = R for all t. DCC not: R_t = alpha + beta * R_{t-1}.

Setting up

Installing new packages

ccgarch package

The ccgarch package has been recently removed from the CRAN repository, however its source code is still available in the CRAN archives:

  • https://cran.r-project.org/src/contrib/Archive/ccgarch/

Hence, we can install directly with:

install.packages("https://cran.r-project.org/src/contrib/Archive/ccgarch/ccgarch_0.2.3.tar.gz", 
                 repos = NULL)

rmgarch package

install.packages("rmgarch") # more flexible for DCC models

Additional information:

  • https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rmgarch/vignettes/The_rmgarch_models.pdf

Example #1 - univariate volatility modelling with GARCH extensions

We will start with estimating the univariate AR(1)-EGARCH(2,1) model for S&P500 and NASDAQ returns (separately) with the rugarch package.

First, we prepare the object with model specification:

ar1egarch21mt.spec <- 
  ugarchspec(# variance equation
    variance.model = list(model = "eGARCH", 
                          garchOrder = c(2,1)),
    # mean equation
    mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(1,0), 
                      include.mean = FALSE,
                      archm = TRUE, archpow = 1), 
    # assumed distribution of errors
    distribution.model = "std") # std = t-Student

Next, we fit both models separately.

SP500.ar1egarch21mt <- ugarchfit(spec = ar1egarch21mt.spec, 
                                 data = data.US$r_SP500)

NQ.ar1egarch21mt <- ugarchfit(spec = ar1egarch21mt.spec, 
                              data = data.US$r_NQ)

In the next examples, we will apply some multivariate GARCH models.

Example #2 - DCC model with rmgarch package

DCC (Dynamic Conditional Correlation) GARCH for SPP500 and NASDAQ returns with a more flexible estimation function from thermgarch package.

DCC specification - lets use DCC(2,1). For both series we use the AR(1)-EGARCH(2,1)-t specification (the model with in-mean element does not converge).

Let’s define a common specification for volatilities in the same way as we did for univariate models:

ar1egarch21t.spec <- ugarchspec(# variance equation
                                variance.model = list(model = "eGARCH", 
                                                      garchOrder = c(2, 1)),
                                # mean equation
                                mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(1, 0),
                                                  include.mean = FALSE), 
                                # assumed distribution of errors
                                distribution.model = "std") # std = t-Student

Specification for the whole multivariate model:

dcc21.spec <- dccspec(# we need to use 2 specifications as we model 2 variables
                     uspec = multispec( c(ar1egarch21t.spec, 
                                          ar1egarch21t.spec) ), 
                     dccOrder = c(2, 1)) # dynamic corelation model order

Finally, we fit the model:

dcc.fit <- dccfit(dcc21.spec,    # specification
                  data = data.US.ret) # data

Now, we can analyze the results:

When calling in the console, make a plot selection (ESC to exit):

  • 1: Conditional Mean (vs Realized Returns)
  • 2: Conditional Sigma (vs Realized Absolute Returns)
  • 3: Conditional Covariance
  • 4: Conditional Correlation

Further recommendation: the mgarchBEKK package, more details here:

  • https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/mgarchBEKK/mgarchBEKK.pdf

Forecasting the the DCC model:

dcc.forecasts <-
  dccforecast(dcc.fit, 
              n.ahead = 1, 
              n.roll  = 0)

Example #3 - EMWA approach on another dataset

The SIGMA matrix with the EWMA approach.

We will use the data with returns of Hang-Seng index (HK) and Nikkei index (JP).

hkjp <- readRDS("data/hkjp.rds")
hkjp %>% glimpse()
## Rows: 713
## Columns: 3
## $ Date <date> 2006-01-05, 2006-01-06, 2006-01-10, 2006-01-11, 2006-01-12, 2006…
## $ HK   <dbl> 15271.13, 15344.44, 15569.91, 15650.88, 15719.37, 15787.97, 15777…
## $ JP   <dbl> 16425.37, 16428.21, 16124.35, 16363.59, 16445.19, 16454.95, 16268…

Creating log returns:

hkjp$rHK <- diff.xts(log(hkjp$HK))
hkjp$rJP <- diff.xts(log(hkjp$JP))

Plot of returns:

par(mfrow = c(2, 1))
plot(hkjp$Date, hkjp$rHK,
     type = 'l', lwd = 1, col = 'red',   ylab = 'HongKong', xlab = 'Date')
plot(hkjp$Date, hkjp$rJP,
     type = 'l', lwd = 1, col = 'green', ylab = 'Japan',   xlab = 'Date')

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

or alternatively with the gglot2 package:

hkjp %>%
  dplyr::select(Date, rHK, rJP) %>%
  pivot_longer(!Date) %>%
  ggplot(aes(Date, value, col = name)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(name)) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(
    title = "returns of Hong-Kong and Japan equity indices",
    subtitle = paste0("obs = ", nrow(hkjp)),
    caption = "source: data from Tsay(2010), own calculations"
  )

Estimating GARCH(1,1) model with the ugarchFit() function:

spec <- ugarchspec(
  variance.model = list(model = "sGARCH",
                        garchOrder = c(1, 1)),
  mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0, 0), include.mean = T),
  distribution.model = "norm")

rHK.garch11 <- ugarchfit(spec = spec, data = na.omit(hkjp$rHK))

tibble(

Estimation of the DCC model:

dcc.para <- c(0.01, 0.98)
a <- c(0.003, 0.005)
A <- diag(c(0.2, 0.3))
B <- diag(c(0.75, 0.6))
dcc.results <- dcc.estimation(inia     = a,
                              iniA     = A,
                              iniB     = B,
                              ini.dcc  = dcc.para,
                              dvar     = hkjp.mat,
                              model    = "diagonal",
                              method   = "BFGS",
                              gradient = 1,
                              message  = 1)
